● Here's how I see the landscape:

  ---
  The fundamental constraint: file:// blocks fetch()

  Most popular static site search tools (Lunr.js, Pagefind, Algolia DocSearch) generate a JSON index that the page
  fetches at runtime. This silently fails when you open a file directly in a browser — browsers block fetch() and
  XMLHttpRequest for local files by default. So any approach that loads a separate search index file is out, unless you
  start using a local web server.

  That leaves two clean options:

  ---
  Option A — Title/date filtering (simplest, ~20 lines of JS)

  Add a search <input> to index.html that filters the visible <li> items in real-time by matching against .article-title
   and .article-date text.

  - Works perfectly on file://
  - Zero dependencies, instant
  - Limitation: can only find what's already in the list — titles and dates. Can't answer "which day mentioned the
  Compaction API?"

  ---
  Option B — Embedded JSON index (full-text, recommended if you want body search)

  Embed a JS data structure directly inside index.html:

  <script>
  const SEARCH_INDEX = [
    { date: "2026-03-20", title: "Firefox Security…",
      tags: ["security","computer-use"],
      text: "stripped plain-text of all article body content…",
      url: "archives/2026/03/2026-03-20.html" },
    …
  ];
  </script>

  The search JS filters this in-memory array — no fetch() needed. The SKILL.md skill would strip HTML from new entries
  and append to this block on each run.

  - Size: ~2–5 KB per day of prose → ~1 MB/year in index.html. Fine for a local file.
  - Complexity: SKILL.md needs a small extra step; the index can get out of sync if manually edited (fixable with a
  rebuild pass).

  ---
  My suggestion

  Do Option A first — it's one small <input> and a few lines of inline JS, uses your existing CSS variables, and
  requires no skill changes. It covers the "which day was that?" use case.

  Add Option B later when you actually find yourself wanting to search article body text. It's more work but still no
  external dependencies.

  ---
  The four open questions before I'd write any implementation plan:

  1. Scope now: Title+date filtering only, or full-text body search from the start?
  2. UX: Live filter-as-you-type, or search on Enter?
  3. Results display: Hide non-matching rows in place, or show a separate results view?
  4. No-match state: Empty list, or a "no results found" message?

